\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

-type superconductive (SC) proximity effect of uniform pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

 reading as 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Delta_{0}c_{\uparrow}^{\dagger}c_{\downarrow}^{\dagger}+h.c)/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this minimal model, having set a value for the uniform pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}$
\end_inset

, one can then induce a trivial-topological phase transitions just by the
 tuning of the Zeeman field 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 versus the chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 This occurs exactly at the frontier of the critical value 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}^{c}=\sqrt{\mu^{2}+\Delta_{0}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 with the closing and reopening of the band gap, signaling the non symmetry
 protected phase transition.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}>V_{\text{Z}}^{c}$
\end_inset

 the system is in its topological phase maintaining a minigap due to the
 combined affects of Zeeman and SOC and two emergent Majorana zero energy
 modes, topological protected by said minigap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary step up we make to this model is that we replace the unrealistic
 superconductive 
\emph on
uniform
\emph default
 proximity effect term for a self-consistently onsite Hubbard self-energy
 term as described in the previous section.
 Concretely, and within the Nambu tight-binding scheme presented in the
 previous section having defined the spinor 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\check{c}}_{i}=(c_{i\uparrow}\,\,c_{i\downarrow}\,\,c_{i\uparrow}^{\dagger}\,\,c_{i\downarrow}^{\dagger})$
\end_inset

, this amounts to substituting in the Hamiltonian matrix the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}\left[\tau_{y}\otimes\sigma_{y}\right]\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 of Eq.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{eq:seU}}$
\end_inset

).
 The full Hamiltonian matrix reads explicitly as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{H} & =\left(f\delta_{ij}-t\delta_{ij\pm1}\right)\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]\nonumber \\
 & +V_{\text{Z}}\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{z}\right]\delta_{ij}+\frac{\alpha_{\text{R}}}{2a_{0}}\delta_{ij\pm1}^{\pm}\left[\tau_{z}\otimes i\sigma_{y}\right]\label{eq:H}\\
 & +\frac{1}{2}U\left[\text{Tr}\left(\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{ii}\right)\left[\tau_{z}\otimes\sigma_{0}\right]-2\tilde{\boldsymbol{\rho}}_{ij}\right]\delta_{ij}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $f=2t-\mu$
\end_inset

 the band filling (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=2t$
\end_inset

 corresponding to half and zero filling respectively), 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\eta/a_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 the hopping parameter.
 The Kronecker delta terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij\pm1}^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 denote the on-site terms and the 1st neighbors hoppings, front and back.
\end_layout

