\begin_layout Standard
Firstly, we examine the cases of infinite length nanowires since these lay
 out much of the necessary groundwork without muddying it with finite length
 effects.
 Also because it was a lot less numerically expensive.
 Concerning their self-consistent routines, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}\rightarrow\Sigma_{0}\rightarrow H_{0}\rightarrow\rho_{1}\rightarrow\Sigma_{1}\rightarrow...$
\end_inset

, in particular on how to numerically solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 through 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, for the finite case we straight forwardly do a full spectrum diagonalization
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=-i(\epsilon+i\eta-H)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 while for the infinite case we instead do a Schur's factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{dn}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^{+\pi}d\phi f(H(\phi)-\mu I)e^{idn\phi}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 the Bloch phase and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 the Fermi function at zero temperature.
 As a side-note, it it important that one forcefully imposes the BdG symmetries
 on the Hamiltonian on every iteration because numerical errors will progressive
ly drive it to break them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the Lutchyn's minimal model, we focus on how the spectrum, particularly
 the gap and minigap, behaves as a function of Zeeman and chemical potential,
 now with the subtlety of self-consistence.
 Preceding that analysis however, it is convient to have the notion that
 if the on-site Hubbard potential is 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

 then the correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i\uparrow j\downarrow}^{\text{eh}}$
\end_inset

 is favored and the system is superconductive but if 
\begin_inset Formula $U>0$
\end_inset

 then the correlation 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{i\uparrow j\uparrow}^{\text{ee}}-\rho_{i\downarrow j\downarrow}^{\text{ee}})/2$
\end_inset

 is instead favored and the system is ferromagnetic.
 Although 
\begin_inset Formula $U<0$
\end_inset

 is a prerequisite for a non-zero superconductive correlation it alone does
 not guarantee it.
 This can be, for example, due to a strong enough Zeeman effect that forcefully
 magnetizes the system or due to a sufficient large 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 since BCS theory tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{\text{BCS}}\propto\text{exp}[-Ua_{0}n_{\text{1D}}(\mu)]^{-1}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{1D}}$
\end_inset

 being the 1D density of states (DOS) which decreases as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 increases.
\end_layout

